  "prompt": "How do you say thank you in Arabic? Does it depend on who you're speaking to?",
  "response": "In Arabic, there are a few ways to say \"thank you\" depending on the context and level of formality:\n\n1. \"Shukran\" (\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b) - This is the most common and basic way to say \"thank you\" in Arabic. It's used in most situations and is generally appropriate for everyone.\n\n2. \"Shukran Jazilan\" (\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b \u062c\u0632\u064a\u0644\u0627\u064b) - This means \"thank you very much\" and is a bit more formal.\n\n3. If you want to respond to someone's thanks, you can say \"Afwan\" (\u0639\u0641\u0648\u0627\u064b), which means \"you're welcome.\"\n\nThe basic form \"Shukran\" doesn't change based on who you're speaking to, but the tone and context can vary. In more formal or respectful situations, you might add extra words or use a more elaborate phrase.\n\nIf you're speaking to multiple people or want to be extra polite, you might say \"Shukran Lak\" (\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b \u0644\u0643) for a male or \"Shukran Laki\" (\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b \u0644\u0643\u0650) for a female.\n\nThese phrases are used across most Arabic-speaking countries, though there might be slight regional variations.",
